  "text": "-food-based approaches to HFI have emerged as the default option. Municipal-level* interventions to address HFI generally fall into one of three models, [CITATION_1] with many organizations delivering some combination of these: \"charitable\" (e.g., food banks, soup kitchens); \"household improvements and supports\" (e.g., good food boxes, community kitchens, budgeting and cooking skills workshops); and \"community food systems\" (e.g., community gardens, food charters, food policy councils). While these food-based interventions have been adopted as a means to address HFI, many of them also aim to achieve a range of other objectives, such as promoting nutritious food for all, social cohesion and food system sustainability. [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] Rationale and knowledge gaps",
